The Open-Closed Principle (OCP) is a software design principle that states that a class should be open for extension but closed for modification. In other words, you should be able to add new functionality to a class without changing its existing code.

The idea behind the Open-Closed Principle is to design your software in a way that allows you to make changes and add new functionality without breaking existing code. This can help to reduce the risk of introducing bugs and make it easier to maintain and evolve your software over time.

One way to apply the Open-Closed Principle in Go is to use interfaces. An interface is a set of method signatures that define a contract for a class to implement. By using interfaces, you can add new functionality to your software by creating new classes that implement the interface, without having to change the existing code of the classes that use the interface.

For example, consider a simple logging system that has a `Logger` interface with a single `Log` method:


```
type Logger interface {
 Log(message string)
}
```
You could then create a `ConsoleLogger` class that implements the `Logger` interface and writes log messages to the console:


```
type ConsoleLogger struct{}

func (l \*ConsoleLogger) Log(message string) {
 fmt.Println(message)
}
```
Now, if you want to add a new logging destination (e.g. a file), you can create a new class that implements the `Logger` interface and write log messages to the file, without having to change the existing `ConsoleLogger` class:


```
