`std::string_view` is a C++17 feature that provides a lightweight, non-owning view of a string. It allows you to work with strings in a more efficient and convenient way, by avoiding unnecessary string copies and allocations.

The main problem that `std::string_view` solves is the problem of string manipulation and ownership. When working with `std::string` objects, passing strings around by value can result in a large number of unnecessary string copies, which can be both slow and memory-intensive. Additionally, if you need to work with a string for a short period of time, creating a temporary `std::string` object for it can be wasteful.

`std::string_view` provides a way to work with strings without taking ownership of the underlying memory. Instead of creating a new copy of the string, a `std::string_view` object simply holds a pointer to the original memory and a length, allowing you to work with the string without incurring the overhead of a copy.

