One example of a searching algorithm with O(log n) time complexity is the binary search algorithm.

The binary search algorithm works by repeatedly dividing the search interval in half. It compares the target value with the middle element of the array. If the target value is less than the middle element, the search continues in the lower half of the array. If the target value is greater than the middle element, the search continues in the upper half of the array. The search continues until the target value is found or until the search interval is empty.

Here is an example implementation of binary search in C++:


```c++
int binarySearch(const std::vector<int>& arr, int target) {
 int low = 0;
 int high = arr.size() - 1;

 while (low <= high) {
 int mid = (low + high) / 2;
 if (arr[mid] == target) {
 return mid;
 } else if (arr[mid] < target) {
 low = mid + 1;
 } else {
 high = mid - 1;
 }
 }

 return -1; // target not found
}
```
The time complexity of this algorithm is O(log n) as in each step of the while loop, the search interval is divided by half.

Another example of an algorithm that is O(log n) is the binary search tree search algorithm.

Binary Search Tree(BST) is a tree-based data structure in which each node has at most two children, which are referred to as the left child and the right child.

The search operation in a BST starts at the root. If the key to be searched is less than the root, we recur for the left subtree, else we recur for the right subtree. The time complexity of search operation in a BST is O(h) where h is the height of the tree. The height of a balanced binary search tree is O(log n) and this is why the search in a balanced BST is O(log n)

In summary, both Binary Search and Search in a balanced BST are O(log n) algorithms.

