A palindrome is a word, phrase, number, or other sequence of characters which reads the same forward and backward. Examples include "madam" or "racecar".

To check if a word or phrase is a palindrome, you can compare the first and last characters, then the second and second-to-last characters, and so on. If all of the pairs match, the word or phrase is a palindrome.

Here is an example of a function in C++ that checks if a given string is a palindrome:


```sql
bool isPalindrome(string s) {
 int left = 0, right = s.length() - 1;
 while (left < right) {
 if (s[left] != s[right]) {
 return false;
 }
 left++;
 right--;
 }
 return true;
}
```
This function uses two pointers, one starting at the beginning of the string and one starting at the end. It compares the characters at the two pointers, and if they don't match, it returns false. If it makes it through the entire string without finding any mismatched characters, it returns true.

It's worth noting that there are other methods to check for a palindrome, like using stack or recursion, but they are less efficient than the above method.

This problem can be solved by using a hashmap to store the frequency of each character in the string s. Then, iterating through the hashmap and adding the frequency of each character that has an even frequency to the total length of the palindrome. Additionally, if there is at least one character with an odd frequency, the total length of the palindrome can be increased by 1.

Here is an example of the code in C++:


```c
int longestPalindrome(string s) {
 unordered\_map<char, int> freq;
 for (char c : s) {
 freq[c]++;
 }
 int res = 0;
 bool odd_exist = false;
 for (auto [c, f] : freq) {
 res += f / 2 * 2;
 if (f % 2 == 1) {
 odd_exist = true;
 }
 }
 if (odd_exist) {
 res++;
 }
 return res;
}
