The sliding window technique can be used to solve this problem. The approach is to maintain a window of characters in the string and move the window through the string while keeping track of the maximum length of the substring without repeating characters.

Here is an example implementation in C++:


```sql
int lengthOfLongestSubstring(string s) {
 unordered_map<char, int> char_index;
 int max_length = 0;
 int start = 0;
 for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
 if (char_index.count(s[i]) && char_index[s[i]] >= start) {
 start = char_index[s[i]] + 1;
 }
 char_index[s[i]] = i;
 max_length = max(max_length, i - start + 1);
 }
 return max_length;
}
```
This code uses a hash table (unordered\_map in C++) to store the last index of each character in the current window. As the window moves through the string, if a character is encountered that is already in the hash table and the index of that character is greater than or equal to the start of the window, the start of the window is updated to be the last index of that character + 1. The maximum length of the substring is updated at each step by taking the maximum of the current length and the length of the current window.

In this way we keep track of a unique characters in a window, updating the start of the window when a repeat character is encountered and updating the maximum length of the substring whenever a new substring is encountered. The time complexity of this approach is O(n) and the space complexity is O(min(n, m)) where n is the length of the string and m is the size of the character set.

