Multithreading is a feature that allows concurrent execution of two or more parts of a program for maximum utilization of the CPU. Each part of such a program is called a thread. So, threads are lightweight processes within a process. Multithreading support was introduced in C++11. Prior to C++11, we had to use POSIX threads or pthreads library [[3](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/multithreading-in-cpp/)].

