string decodeString(string s) {
 stack<char> st;
 for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
 if (s[i] != ']') {
 st.push(s[i]);
 } else {
 string temp = "";
 while (st.top() != '[') {
 temp = st.top() + temp;
 st.pop();
 }
 st.pop(); // remove the opening bracket
 int count = 0, factor = 1;
 while (!st.empty() && isdigit(st.top())) {
 count += (st.top() - '0') * factor;
 factor *= 10;
 st.pop();
 }
 for (int j = 0; j < count; j++) {
 for (char c : temp) {
 st.push(c);
 }
 }
 }
 }
 string result = "";
 while (!st.empty()) {
 result = st.top() + result;
 st.pop();
 }
 return result;
}

int main() {
 string s = "3[a2[c]]";
 string decoded = decodeString(s);
 cout << decoded << endl;
 return 0;
}
```
This implementation assumes that the input string is well-formed (i.e., it contains a valid number followed by a valid substring enclosed in brackets). If the input string is not well-formed, this algorithm may encounter errors or return an incorrect result.

Here's a simple implementation of binary search in C++:


```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int binarySearch(vector<int> &arr, int l, int r, int x) {
 if (r >= l) {
 int mid = l + (r - l) / 2;

 if (arr[mid] == x)
 return mid;

 if (arr[mid] > x)
 return binarySearch(arr, l, mid - 1, x);

 return binarySearch(arr, mid + 1, r, x);
 }
 return -1;
}

int main() {
 vector<int> arr = {2, 5, 7, 10, 15, 20};
 int n = arr.size();
 int x = 10;
 int result = binarySearch(arr, 0, n - 1, x);
 if (result == -1)
 cout << "Element is not present in array";
 else
 cout << "Element is present at index " << result;
 return 0;
}
```
In this implementation, we define a `binarySearch` function that takes in an array `arr`, the starting and ending indices `l` and `r`, and the element to search for `x`. We first check if the ending index is greater than or equal to the starting index. If it is, we calculate the middle index and check if the element at the middle index is the element we are looking for. If it is, we return the middle index. If it is not, we check whether the element at the middle index is greater than the element we are looking for. If it is, we call the `binarySearch` function again on the left half of the array. If it is not, we call the `binarySearch` function again on the right half of the array. If the ending index is less than the starting index, we return -1 to indicate that the element is not present in the array.

In the `main` function, we create an array and call the `binarySearch` function on it to search for a particular element. If the element is found, the function returns the index at which the element is located. If the element is not found, the function returns -1.

